  "has_voiceover": false,
  "description": "Don't be in a rush to get screwed",
  "body_html": "<p>Everyone in the world seems to tell you to assume more risk - both from career and personal standpoints. Here is some shit I keep hearing, just everywhere </p><ul><li><p>leave your country and move away.</p></li><li><p>leave your current partner to find a better partner.</p></li><li><p>quit your job and do x [startup / mission / whatever]. </p></li><li><p>quit your job and travel the world in a dangerous place. </p></li><li><p>leave your main research program and try a risky one.</p></li><li><p>quit college.</p></li></ul><p>I think this advice is mostly useless and stupid. </p><p>You should not default to want to take more risk in life for no reason. </p><p>The first reason is the obvious one. This is because decisions with risk can go badly. Sometimes catastrophically. Things can go wrong by chance, like doing a BASE jump. Or, if you are uncomfortable taking risks, then in high stakes situations you won\u2019t be relaxed enough to make good decisions. </p><p>So if this is the case, why do people love advertising taking risk so much? Why do people espouse it as strong advice?</p><p>This is because most people who tell you to take risk are either:</p><ul><li><p>People who have irrationally [more downside than upside] taken risk then got lucky, and so then start spreading the risk taking world view. OR: </p></li><li><p><strong>They are people who can afford to take risk</strong> (i.e. they have rich families, a stable immigration situation, live in a developed country, or live in SF). </p></li></ul><p>A lot of people are <strong>not</strong> in the latter camp. That\u2019s fine, just a fact of life. If you are outside your home country then your visa is likely dependent on a job with a required minimum salary. Or most people have kids and a family they need to support.</p><p>I myself only started to take more risks when I could afford to. I built some savings until my immigration situation got more stable. If I left my job prematurely and things didn\u2019t work out I\u2019d have to go back to Malaysia, which would be a fail. So it was reasonable to wait on a safety net before taking risks like spending more time blogging and moving to riskier jobs.</p><p>And as you may notice, my following has got a bit bigger, so I\u2019m more comfortable writing edgier stuff and doing wilder science on this blog. </p><p>I\u2019m not saying you need to afford to take risks to start taking them. </p><p>I personally just became more comfortable when I could. I now like the strategy where I spend 70% of my time doing things that are safe and reliable, and 30% of my time doing potshots, like bioreactors. And so if I can take more risks whilst being more comfortable, why not? </p>",
  "truncated_body_text": "Everyone in the world seems to tell you to assume more risk - both from career and personal standpoints. Here is some shit I keep hearing, just everywhere",
